---
// Privacy — plain-language note on data handling.
// Covers only what's actually true today: Web3Forms contact form, hCaptcha, click-to-load
// YouTube embeds (player + cookies wait for click; the preview thumbnail loads from YouTube on
// render), localStorage theme preference, and no analytics.
// Keep this in sync with the real implementation — brand-truth gate governs copy here.
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { CONTACT_EMAIL } from '../consts';
import { withBase } from '../lib/link';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Privacy"
  description="How Wisco Radio Labs handles data — no tracking, no analytics. The contact form goes through Web3Forms and hCaptcha; blog video thumbnails load from YouTube. Details inside."
>
  <section class="section container privacy-section">

    <h1 class="page-title">Privacy &amp; Data Handling</h1>
    <p class="page-lead">
      Short version: no tracking, no ad tech, no analytics. The main thing that moves is what
      you send through the contact form — and the few third parties involved (the form processor,
      its spam check, and YouTube for video thumbnails) are spelled out below.
    </p>
    <p class="last-updated">Last updated: 2026-07-09</p>

    <div class="privacy-prose">

      <h2>The contact form</h2>
      <p>
        If you use the contact form, it collects your name, email address, subject, and
        message. That gets sent to <strong>Web3Forms</strong> — a third-party form
        processor — which delivers it to my email. Nothing is stored on this site.
        I use it only to reply to you.
      </p>

      <h2>Blog comments</h2>
      <p>
        Comments go through the same <strong>Web3Forms</strong> form processor as the
        contact form, protected by the same <strong>hCaptcha</strong>. Every comment is
        <strong>held for review</strong> — I read and approve each one by hand before it
        appears; nothing publishes automatically. The optional email field on the comment
        form is used only to let you know if someone replies to your comment — it is
        <strong>never published</strong>, never stored in this site's public code, and
        never appears on the page. Comment submissions are processed by Web3Forms and
        forwarded to me by email; Web3Forms' published policy allows them to retain
        submission data for up to 3 years before permanent deletion (their dashboard
        shows me the last 30 days of it), the same as any contact-form submission.
      </p>
      <p>
        An approved comment (your display name and the words you wrote) becomes part of
        this site's <strong>public git history, permanently</strong> — the same way every
        other change to this site is tracked. If you'd like a comment removed later, use
        the <a href={withBase('/contact/')}>contact page</a>; I can take it off the live
        site, but be aware the text will still exist somewhere in that history (this is
        true of anything committed to a public git repository, not specific to comments).
      </p>

      <h2>Spam protection (hCaptcha)</h2>
      <p>
        The form uses <strong>hCaptcha</strong> to keep bots out. Completing the challenge
        may share some technical data with Intuition Machines (the company behind hCaptcha)
        to verify you're human. See their
        <a href="https://www.hcaptcha.com/privacy" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">privacy policy</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Video</h2>
      <p>
        Blog videos use a click-to-load wrapper: the YouTube player doesn't load, and YouTube
        sets no cookies, until you click play. Before that, the one thing fetched from YouTube is
        the preview thumbnail image (from its image servers), so YouTube does see your IP for that
        image. Press play and the full player loads, with YouTube's own cookies and policies.
      </p>

      <h2>Tracking</h2>
      <p>
        None. No analytics, no tracking cookies, no ad tech.
      </p>

      <h2>Your browser</h2>
      <p>
        The only thing stored in your browser is your light/dark theme preference —
        saved in localStorage, on your device. That's it.
      </p>

      <h2>Questions</h2>
      <p>
        Anything unclear? Use the <a href={withBase('/contact/')}>Contact page</a>
        {CONTACT_EMAIL && <>{' '}or email me at <a href={`mailto:${CONTACT_EMAIL}`}>{CONTACT_EMAIL}</a></>}.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .privacy-section {
    padding-bottom: var(--space-12);
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: var(--fs-h1);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
  }

  .page-lead {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: var(--fs-body);
    max-width: 60ch;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
  }

  .last-updated {
    font-size: var(--fs-small);
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  /* Prose body: capped width for readability, consistent spacing between sections. */
  .privacy-prose {
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  .privacy-prose h2 {
    font-size: var(--fs-h3);
    margin: var(--space-8) 0 var(--space-3);
    color: var(--text);
  }

  /* Remove top margin from the first section heading so it sits flush under the date. */
  .privacy-prose h2:first-child {
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .privacy-prose p {
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-4);
    font-size: var(--fs-body);
  }

  .privacy-prose a {
    color: var(--brand-ink);
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  .privacy-prose a:hover {
    color: var(--brand);
  }

  .privacy-prose a:focus-visible {
    outline: 3px solid var(--focus-ring);
    outline-offset: 2px;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
  }
</style>
